Short Answer Questions

Q1. What are the differences between atrioventricularvalves and semilunar valves?

Q1. What are the differences between atrioventricular valvesand semilunar valves?

  • Atrioventricular
    • Separate the atria and the ventricles
    • Prevent backflow into the atria when ventricles contract
    • Papillary muscle provide tension during ventricular systoleprevent prolapse into the atria
    • Tricuspid
    • Mitral
  • Semilunar valves
    • Separate the great vessels and the ventricles
    • Prevent backflow into the ventricles
    • Closed by backflow of blood (which fills sinuses) afterventricular contraction
    • Aortic
    • Pulmonary

Q2. What do coronary arteries do?

Q2. What do coronary arteries do?

  • Provide blood supply to the Myocardium
    • Come from the first branches of the aorta (at theproximal part of the ascending aorta)
  • Cardiac veins collect deoxygenated blood from themyocardium and return it to the right atrium via thecoronary sinus

Q3.What is cardiac output? Describe the two factorsthat determine cardiac output.

Q3.What is cardiac output? Describe the two factorsthat determine cardiac output.

Cardiac output is the total volume of blood ejected byeach ventricle in a minute.

It is the product of the (heart rate) x (stroke volume).

Stroke volume is the volume of blood expelled by aventricle on eachsystolic stroke.

Long Answer Questions

Q1. Describe blood flow through the chambers of the heartduring the cardiac cycle.

  • Late diastole: both sets of chambers are relaxed andventricles fill passively
  • Atrial systole: atrial contraction forces a small amount ofadditional blood into ventricles
  • Isovolumic ventricular contraction: ventricularcontraction pushes AV valves closed but does not createenough pressure to open semilunar valves
  • Ventricular ejection: as ventricular pressure rises andexceeds pressure in the arteries, the semilunar valves openand blood is ejected
  • Isovolumic ventricular relaxation: as the ventriclesrelax, pressure in the ventricles falls, blood flows back intocups of semilunar valves and snaps them closed

Q2. What is the Electrocardiogram (ECG)? What are thethree major waves?

Q2.What is the Electrocardiogram (ECG)? What are thethree major waves?

  • ECG is a body surface recording that measures theaverage extracellular potentials of the whole heart
  • Three major waves
    • P wave
      • Atrial depolarisation
    • QRS complex
      • Ventricular depolarisation
    • T wave
      • Ventricular repolarisation

Q2. What are the heart sounds? What do theycorrespond to in the cardiac cycle?

Q2. What are the heart sounds? What do theycorrespond to in the cardiac cycle?

  • Turbulent blood flow and vibrations create sound,which occurs twice during the cardiac cycle
  • First heart sound
    • Closure ofatrio-ventricular valves (mitral and tricuspid)
  • Second heart sound
    • Closure of semilunar valves (aortic and pulmonary)
